answers.body_markdown:
Use [`Objects.requireNonNull(Object)`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Objects.html#requireNonNull(T)) for that.

&gt; Checks that the specified object reference is not null. This method is designed primarily for doing parameter validation in methods and constructors, [...]

In your case that would be:

```java
public void useObject(CustomObject customObject) {
    object = customObject.getObject();
    Objects.requireNonNull(object); // throws NPE if object is null
    // do stuff with object
}
```

This function is made for what you want to do: explicitly mark what is not to be `null`. The benefit is that you find `null`-values right where they should not occur. You will have [less troubles debugging](https://stackoverflow.com/q/45632920/12323248) problems caused by `null`s that are passed somewhere where they shouldn&#39;t be.

Another benefit is the flexibility when using this function in contrast to `assert`. While `assert` is a keyword for checking a boolean value, `Objects.requireNonNull(Object)` is a function and can be embedded in code much easier.

```java
Foo foo = Objects.requireNonNull(service.fetchFoo());

// you cannot write it in one line.
Bar bar = service.fetchBar();
assert bar != null;
```

```java
service.foo(Objects.requireNonNull(service.getBar()));

// you cannot write it in one line.
Bar bar = service.getBar();
assert bar != null;
service.foo(bar);
```

Keep in mind that `Objects.requireNonNull(Object)` is only for `null`-checking while `assert` is for general assertions. So `assert` has [different purposes](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/language/assert.html): primarily testing. It has to be enabled, so you can enable it for testing and disable it in production. Use it to seperate testing-only-tests from tests, or rather checks, that are meant for production-code too.

